{"author":{"id":"2d08e4816aca0a07db9878f126b0e7f6d6f1362eb9bc4804be6b33ff8d0a19ec"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1710464553,"nonce":"UJG6fmRp0co2wv0wfEruYlijLEs=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOJl1IZM53IgUx","github-url":"https://github.com/nikitabobko/AeroSpace/issues/183#issuecomment-1998718257"},"message":"\u003e If you can move the current window to the left in the current workspace, do it! Otherwise, move the window to the monitor in the left (wrapping around)\n\nI agree that a workflow like this should be supported. Right now, it's, unfortunately, not supported\n\n\u003e Unfortunately, that doesn't work, since `aerospace move left` does not fail when it can't move.\n\nIt doesn't fail because the mental model is different. When you \"move window out\", an implicit container is created. (See the \"implicit container example\" in the docs https://nikitabobko.github.io/AeroSpace/commands#move)\n\nCreating an implicit container is always successful\n\n---\n\n\u003e Another way to solve it would be to make move to work similarly to the [focus command](https://nikitabobko.github.io/AeroSpace/commands#focus) (with boundaries and boundaries actions).\n\n I need more time to think about it, but right now I agree. The synopsis could look like:\n```\naerospace move\n  --move-boundaries (workspace|all-monitors-outer-frame)\n  --boundaries-action (stop|create-implicit-container)\n  (left|down|up|right)\n```\n\nthen your desired workflow could be achieved in the following way: `aerospace move --move-boundaries all-monitors-outer-frame`","files":null},{"type":6,"timestamp":1710464776,"nonce":"bvYX2EvaLlNzQ1K4ahqtyrQFtFE=","metadata":{"github-id":"UCE_lALOJl1IZM53IgUxzkIX3Ng"},"target":"a8e55a8c650a7bf7b166e932233a85d6f43abd5ff450176e88b90ff569d1381e","message":"\u003e If you can move the current window to the left in the current workspace, do it! Otherwise, move the window to the monitor in the left (wrapping around)\n\nI agree that a workflow like this should be supported. Right now, it's, unfortunately, not supported\n\n\u003e Unfortunately, that doesn't work, since `aerospace move left` does not fail when it can't move.\n\nIt doesn't fail because the mental model is different. When you \"move window out\", an implicit container is created. (See the \"implicit container example\" in the docs https://nikitabobko.github.io/AeroSpace/commands#move)\n\nCreating an implicit container is always successful\n\n---\n\n\u003e Another way to solve it would be to make move to work similarly to the [focus command](https://nikitabobko.github.io/AeroSpace/commands#focus) (with boundaries and boundaries actions).\n\n I need more time to think about it, but right now I agree. The synopsis could look like:\n```\naerospace move\n  --move-boundaries (workspace|all-monitors-outer-frame)\n  --boundaries-action (stop|create-implicit-container)\n  (left|down|up|right)\n```\n\nthen your desired workflow could be achieved in the following way: `aerospace move --move-boundaries all-monitors-outer-frame`\n\nOne more alternative could be to introduce `--no-create-implicit-container`. But this alternative can be generalized with `--boundaries-action fail` (`fail` is like `stop` but with non-zero exit code)","files":null}]}